{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-chapter-level-2-chapter-level-2-tsx","path":"/topics/retinal-detachment/background-information/definition/","result":{"pageContext":{"chapter":{"id":"4d268a45-69b2-5f94-9f83-4e3bde2a12b8","slug":"definition","fullItemName":"Definition","depth":2,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field f88d4cdd-dc2c-41fa-b586-21c8475c0411 --><h2>What is it?</h2><!-- end field f88d4cdd-dc2c-41fa-b586-21c8475c0411 -->","summary":"","htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item fa77a13d-d3ed-46b7-ac9e-9bcb3f982d9a --><!-- begin field 848635dd-dfca-4721-a5cc-60d0c4106875 --><ul><li><strong>Retinal detachment </strong>refers to the separation of the inner neurosensory retina from the underlying retinal pigment epithelium, which allows liquified vitreous fluid to accumulate in the subretinal space [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/retinal-detachment/references/\">Shah, 2014</a>].<ul><li>The separation results in progressive loss of vision leading to permanent visual loss in the affected eye, if the detachment extends across the macula [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/retinal-detachment/references/\">Gariano and Kim, 2004</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/retinal-detachment/references/\">Kang and Luff, 2008</a>].</li></ul></li><li><strong>Retinal tears or breaks </strong>often precede full retinal detachment and may form due to vitreoretinal traction causing a small, localized defect in the neurosensory retina, without an extensive amount of subretinal fluid [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/retinal-detachment/references/\">Sharma, 2015</a>].<ul><li>About 50% of people with untreated symptomatic retinal breaks will progress to retinal detachment [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/retinal-detachment/references/\">Royal College of Ophthalmologists, 2010</a>].</li></ul></li><li><strong>Posterior vitreous detachment </strong>may lead to retinal detachment by causing one or more retinal tears. This is when the vitreous fluid shrinks and separates from the retina as part of the normal ageing process.<ul><li>By 80 years of age, up to 86% of people develop a partial or complete posterior vitreous detachment, compared with 10% of people less than 60 years of age [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/retinal-detachment/references/\">D'Amico, 2008</a>].</li><li>People with symptomatic posterior vitreous detachment have a 10–15% risk of developing retinal breaks [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/retinal-detachment/references/\">D'Amico, 2008</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/retinal-detachment/references/\">Kang and Luff, 2008</a>].</li></ul></li><li><strong>There are three types of retinal detachment </strong>[<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/retinal-detachment/references/\">Gariano and Kim, 2004</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/retinal-detachment/references/\">Kang and Luff, 2008</a>]<strong>:</strong><ul><li><strong>Rhegmatogenous </strong>(the commonest form) — as the vitreous shrinks and partly separates from the retinal surface, a retinal tear or break may develop. Continuing traction by the vitreous on the retinal surface allows fluid to enter the subretinal space, causing retinal detachment.</li><li><strong>Exudative </strong>— this is caused by leakage of fluid into the subretinal space, often due to inflammatory conditions such as uveitis, or malignant conditions such as choroidal melanoma. Treatment of the underlying disease often results in resolution of the retinal detachment, without the need for surgery.</li><li><strong>Tractional </strong>— this is most commonly seen in people with proliferative diabetic retinopathy, where abnormal vasculature causes contraction of the vitreous which then pulls on the underlying retina. Unlike a rhegmatogenous detachment, there is no retinal break.</li></ul></li></ul><!-- end field 848635dd-dfca-4721-a5cc-60d0c4106875 --><!-- end item fa77a13d-d3ed-46b7-ac9e-9bcb3f982d9a -->","topic":{"id":"9be2cb0d-8648-5694-a09c-292ca1ced19e","topicId":"e3f75bdf-a207-4239-9931-367d38a9b7d6","topicName":"Retinal detachment","slug":"retinal-detachment","lastRevised":"Last revised in August 2019","chapters":[{"id":"842ff08c-c002-50cd-bab2-348ba3e67be0","fullItemName":"Summary","slug":"summary","subChapters":[]},{"id":"98f29b98-1286-5c16-a606-4cd90cc70465","fullItemName":"Have I got the right topic?","slug":"have-i-got-the-right-topic","subChapters":[]},{"id":"873d5520-2d22-5b9d-bd04-6d9112dc82ee","fullItemName":"How up-to-date is this topic?","slug":"how-up-to-date-is-this-topic","subChapters":[{"id":"3b54abb3-d415-51e3-996b-1d6e3bcc3d3b","slug":"changes","fullItemName":"Changes"},{"id":"0aa87cea-a601-54db-9dcb-ec3117e7098a","slug":"update","fullItemName":"Update"}]},{"id":"dbe4b4fd-c326-5686-bd9a-71905fc13c76","fullItemName":"Goals and outcome measures","slug":"goals-outcome-measures","subChapters":[{"id":"9f38c5e9-5edd-56fa-a740-0d19004a69af","slug":"goals","fullItemName":"Goals"},{"id":"5960233a-64c2-5a35-95ea-6a44ae788808","slug":"outcome-measures","fullItemName":"Outcome measures"},{"id":"e506d9ce-54a0-57f2-b4d1-49bb28e3d283","slug":"audit-criteria","fullItemName":"Audit criteria"},{"id":"0ce8a869-7cf6-588c-b609-d5a90fa6adf0","slug":"qof-indicators","fullItemName":"QOF indicators"},{"id":"a1808dfe-2608-5274-a314-61a4054cb431","slug":"qipp-options-for-local-implementation","fullItemName":"QIPP - Options for local implementation"},{"id":"6148c790-0603-5594-9e2f-9d1a8bdaab45","slug":"nice-quality-standards","fullItemName":"NICE quality standards"}]},{"id":"17128c85-3baa-5f71-a71e-69028c5e8e6a","fullItemName":"Background information","slug":"background-information","subChapters":[{"id":"4d